1. Manual Page (man sysopctl)
The manual page provides users with detailed information about how to use the sysopctl command.

CODE:

.TH SYOPCTL 1 "October 2024"
.SH NAME
sysopctl \- System Operations Control
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sysopctl
[\fIcommand\fR] [\fIoptions\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
sysopctl is a command-line tool for managing system resources, processes, and health on Linux systems. It provides a user-friendly interface for common system administration tasks.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B service list
List all active services on the system. This command outputs a list similar to the output of `systemctl list-units --type=service`.

.TP
.B service start \fI<service-name>\fR
Start the specified system service. The command outputs a status message confirming the start of the service.

.TP
.B service stop \fI<service-name>\fR
Stop the specified system service. The command outputs a status message confirming the stop of the service.

.TP
.B system load
Display the current system load averages, similar to the output of the `uptime` command.

.TP
.B disk usage
Show disk usage statistics for all mounted filesystems, similar to the `df -h` command.

.TP
.B process monitor
Display real-time process activity, similar to the `top` or `htop` commands.

.TP
.B logs analyze
Summarize recent critical log entries using `journalctl`.

.TP
.B backup \fI<path>\fR
Initiate a backup of the specified path using `rsync`. Outputs a message confirming the backup initiation.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B --help
Display a help message with a brief overview of command usage and available commands.

.TP
.B --version
Display the version information of the sysopctl command.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B sysopctl service list
Lists all running services on the system.

.TP
.B sysopctl service start apache2
Starts the Apache web server.

.TP
.B sysopctl disk usage
Shows disk usage statistics.

.TP
.B sysopctl logs analyze
Analyzes and shows critical log entries.

.SH VERSION
This is version 0.1.0 of sysopctl.


2. Help Option Implementation:
BASH SCRIPT:

#!/bin/bash

function display_help {
  echo "sysopctl - System Operations Control"
  echo "Usage: sysopctl [command] [options]"
  echo
  echo "Commands:"
  echo "  service list             List all active services"
  echo "  service start <service>  Start a specified service"
  echo "  service stop <service>   Stop a specified service"
  echo "  system load              View current system load averages"
  echo "  disk usage               Check disk usage statistics"
  echo "  process monitor          Monitor system processes in real-time"
  echo "  logs analyze             Analyze recent critical log entries"
  echo "  backup <path>           Backup specified files or directories"
  echo
  echo "Options:"
  echo "  --help                   Display this help message"
  echo "  --version                Show the version information"
}

# Main script logic
case "$1" in
  --help)
    display_help
    ;;
  --version)
    echo "sysopctl version 0.1.0"
    ;;
  # Add your existing command cases here
  *)
    echo "Usage: sysopctl [command] [options]"
    ;;
esac

Summary
Manual Page: Provides detailed command usage and examples for users accessing man sysopctl.
Help Option: Displays a quick help message when the user runs sysopctl --help.
These contents should help users understand how to use the sysopctl command effectively.
